      "detail": "3rd in AL East",
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The Blue Jays clawed back late Sunday night in Minneapolis - only to watch Justin Topa slam the door with a slick 4-6-3 double play - as the Twins escaped with a <strong>4-3 gut-punch win</strong>, splitting a four-game set that Toronto had owned for three days straight. Now sitting at 16-18, third in the AL East but a stark 7 games back of the Yankees, the Jays' trajectory screams mediocrity - a one-game skid after torching Minnesota's bullpen for 11 runs Friday and 7 more Saturday. Vladimir Guerrero Jr. went 1-for-5 in the finale, steady but not scorching, while the real dagger came when Twins starter Joe Ryan departed early with elbow soreness - though it was Andrew Morris who blanked Toronto for 3 2/3 innings to steal the night. No major Blue Jays injuries surfaced, but this road stumble stings with the division stretching thin. <strong>Tonight's tilt at the Rays - 5:40 PM ET - demands a rebound</strong>, or the hunt for wild-card seed No. 7 turns into a crawl.",
        "updated": "Updated May 4, 2026"
      },
